<subSubSection type="materials_examined">
<paragraph pageId="73" pageNumber="74">
The type of 
<taxonomicName class="Arachnida" family="Trhypochthoniidae" genus="Trhypochthoniellus" genus.bestMatchDistance="49" genus.bestMatchVote="2" genus.innerRound="1" genus.outerRound="1" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sarcoptiformes" pageId="73" pageNumber="74" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="badius">T. badius</taxonomicName>
is no more present in the Collection. There is a slide (110. 217/31) from Florence (Cascine), and a specimen in the Acarotheca italica; in the Oudemans Collection there is also an &quot; Acarotheca &quot; slide.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph pageId="73" pageNumber="74">The original specimens were collected in moss in a flowerpot in Florence; this moss was possibly Sphagnum, for afterwards the species has been recorded from bogs.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="description">
<paragraph pageId="73" pageNumber="74">
The specimens studied by me are damaged; the dorsal hairs are different from those in 
<taxonomicName class="Arachnida" family="Trhypochthoniidae" genus="Trhypochthonius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sarcoptiformes" pageId="73" pageNumber="74" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Trhypochthonius</taxonomicName>
. The species has a characteristic chestnutbrown colour.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
